newDescription: This project involves building a BBS (Bulletin Board System) while following a set of specific rules. The View System Logs menu item will contain a list of all commands typed into the BBS. The FidoNET menu will mimic the Fidonet protocol, with two menu items for sending and checking mail, as well as a title message displaying how many unread messages there are. Fake FidoNET unread emails will be randomly generated every 4th command. The Door Games menu will be generated based on 10 games of that era, and the BBS name will be "StarGazer". BBS users can respond to FidoNET Emails, and their accounts will remember all conversation history. Finally, every menu page except the main menu will have a "Back to Main Menu" option, and all responses must be within a code block. The BBS will not generate any response in the chat until the command "STARTBBS" is typed, and all rules must be followed for every command.

newTitle: Launch Your Full-Stack React and Django App on AWS Using Docker
newDescription:
Welcome to the guide for launching your full-stack React and Django app on AWS using Docker. Please respond only in English. The following steps will walk you through the process and help you ensure that everything is set up correctly. You will use Docker and AWS to launch your app. If you encounter any issues during this process, refer to the troubleshooting tips or common issues provided in the documentation or seek additional assistance as needed.

To start, follow the steps below:

Step 1: Security Group - Create a new security group in AWS for the EC2 instance and configure it to allow HTTP and SSH traffic.

Step 2: EC2 Instance - Start an EC2 instance, select the security group created in Step 1, allow SSH traffic from your IP, create a new keypair ".pem" file, and download it to your local machine. Then, put the .pem file inside your root project file and run the chmod command given from the instance GUI page.

Step 3: Docker Installation - Install Docker and Docker Compose on the EC2 instance.

Step 4: Docker Configuration - Change all Docker usernames in the ./build-and-push-images.sh and ./docker-compose.prod.yml files.Step 5: Docker Build and Push - Run ./build-and-push-images.sh <MY_EC2_IP_ADDR> <a VERSION you want>.

Step 6: Copy Files to EC2 Instance - Copy the necessary files to the EC2 instance by running the following commands in your local terminal:

scp -i "fullstack.pem" ./setup-ec2.sh <your ec2 instance name>:/home/ec2-user
scp -i "fullstack.pem" ./run-compose-prod.sh <your ec2 instance name>:/home/ec2-user
scp -i "fullstack.pem" ./docker-compose.prod.yml <your ec2 instance name>:/home/ec2-user

Step 7: Verify File Transfer - SSH into your EC2 instance and run "ls" to ensure all files are copied over to the EC2 instance.

Step 8: Django Configuration - Configure the Django app to use environment variables for sensitive information like the SECRET_KEY, instead of hard-coding them in the code.

Step 9: Setup EC2 Instance - Run ./setup-ec2.sh inside your EC2 terminal.

Step 10: SSH into EC2 Instance - Exit your EC2 terminal, SSH into your EC2 instance, and run ./run-compose-prod.sh "<SECRET_KEY>" False <NEW_VERSION>.Step 11: Launch App - Go to the IP address in your browser (ensure it didn't default to https and you're on the http site).

Please do not hesitate to ask any Docker-related questions during the process. Good luck with launching your app on AWS using Docker!"
